Nikolai Makarov completed his project in the theory of 2D DysonÆs gas ensembles supported by the NSF grant DMS-1101735. During the funding period, the research was focused on several fundamental open questions concerning the classical and quantum aspects of the theory, as well as on the relations to the Coulomb gas formalism in conformal field theory.

The PI accomplished the main goals of the project and achieved a significant progress in the following problems of analysis and mathematical physics related to DysonÆs gas theory:

(i)  computation of the (quasi) classical limit of DysonÆs ensembles, derivation of the (Hele-Shaw  type) equations for the evolution of equilibrium measure;

(ii)  characterization of local equilibrium droplets,  applications to  the inverse problem of potential theory;

(iii) complete description of the topology of algebraic droplets and quadrature domains, applications to gravitational lensing;

(iv) Gaussian field convergence of fluctuations in the random normal matrix model;

(v)  rescaling of WardÆs identities in DysonÆs ensembles and the universality laws for the distribution of eigenvalues near the boundary points of the droplet;

(vi) mathematical justification of the Coulomb gas formalism in conformal field theory.

The results and methods of the project have had an impact on several areas of mathematics: potential theory (the discovery of Hele-Shaw flows in equilibrium dynamics, the theory of local equilibrium droplets, the relation between quadrature domains and local droplets),  complex analysis (the existence of certain type of extremal univalent functions,  the new construction of harmonic  polynomials with the maximal number of roots and their rational analogues), and random matrices (several key results concerning normal matrix model, the development of the new technique  -  the rescaled WardÆs identities).  As an important by-product, a new type of conformal dynamical systems associated with quadrature domains and the corresponding Schwarz reflections was discovered. Also, some results and ideas of the project may be of interest to theoretical physicists working in conformal field theory, quantum Hall effect, non-equilibrium growth phenomena, and disordered systems.

The project provided research and training opportunities for several graduate students and postdocs. Makarov developed and taught three new graduate courses at Caltech: "Coulomb gas in 2D", "Mathematical introduction to conformal field theory", and "Quadrature domains". Three of his graduate students successfully defended their PhD theses.  In addition, the PI helped organize two long term programs and a conference on topics closely related to this project.



